Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| Usage | Pattern | Replacement |
|-------|---------|-------------|
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue execution | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` in Stop | Timeout enforcement | `Thread.Join(timeout)` |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — migrated from ThreadAbortException handler
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — just loop back and the while-condition exits
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time. Unlike .NET Framework, there is
            // no way to forcibly kill it. Log a warning — see pitfall notes.
            Console.Error.WriteLine("Worker thread did not exit within timeout.");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

**1. `GetNextItem()` must accept the token.** If it blocks (e.g., on a `BlockingCollection` or socket), cancellation won't take effect until it returns. Fix:

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework) — blocks indefinitely
var item = _queue.Take();

// After (.NET 8) — wakes up on cancellation
var item = _queue.Take(token);  // throws OperationCanceledException
```

**2. No force-kill exists.** `Thread.Abort()` has no equivalent in .NET 8 — it throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. If `GetNextItem` calls uncooperative code that truly can't accept a token, move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`.

**3. `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`.** Always dispose it. The class now implements `IDisposable` to handle this.

**4. The `when` filter matters.** `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` avoids accidentally swallowing cancellations from unrelated tokens.

**5. `Thread.Sleep` in the loop (if any)** won't respond to cancellation. Replace with:
```csharp
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(500));
```

## What Was Removed and Why

| Removed | Why | Replacement |
|---------|-----|-------------|
| `volatile bool _running` | Redundant — `CancellationToken` handles signaling | `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8 | `_cts.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown in .NET 8 | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8 | Not needed — cooperative model doesn't rethrow |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | Not cancellation-aware | `_workerThread.Join(timeout)` |

The key paradigm shift: .NET Framework could **forcibly inject** an exception into any thread. .NET 8 requires **cooperative cancellation** — your code must voluntarily check the token at regular intervals and in every blocking call.
